  "body": "**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**\r\n**Feature**\r\n\r\nAfter reading about [context API ](https://reactjs.org/docs/context.html) I've tried to use it in a somewhat more complex why than it's shown in the docs, and the docs weren't clear enough about what can be passed, and if `value` is the **only** attribute that can be used.\r\n\r\nMy immediate try after reading the docs was thinking that _ANY_ attribute that I put inside the `<ContextProvider>` will be passed to the consumer. I saw that it's not the case. \r\n\r\n\r\n## Example:\r\n\r\n````\r\nconst {Provider, Consumer} = React.createContext({});\r\n\r\n<ContextProvider value={foo.value} action={this.updateValue}>\r\n        <Child />\r\n</ContextProvider>\r\n````\r\n\r\nI have a deep deep child (inside `<Child>`) where I would like to pass some value and some callback.\r\n`action` is `undefined` in the _Consumer_:\r\n\r\n````\r\n<ContextConsumer>\r\n        {(value, action) => (\r\n        <button onClick={()=> action(value + 1)}>Click to INC: {value}</button>\r\n        )}\r\n</ContextConsumer>\r\n````\r\n\r\nI don't understand why can't React pass all the attributes to the consumer, as-is. \r\nwhy only `value` was chosen as the only attribute to be passed?\r\n",
